document.title: Head Start Early Learning Outcomes Framework

0C6FE23F525048D183B3160181711FC6.description: Identifies and follows basic safety rules with adult guidance and support, such as transportation and street safety practices.

EC937980DB3F4C74B2E3B53B77E38C5A.description: Identifies, avoids, and alerts others to danger, such as keeping a safe distance from swings.

6E6997FF284947E48CCB6464144EA5E0.description: Shows awareness of a growing number of personal safety practices and routines. Looks to adults for support in enacting these.

D116A960F05F446A9526F5DDAD601B16.description: Child demonstrates knowledge of personal safety practices and routines.

0D7105A5CCBD4341858670526A11810A.description: Moderates food consumption based on awareness of own hunger and fullness.

CD96657344264F50BE4CB94694D18821.description: Demonstrates basic understanding that eating a variety of foods helps the body grow and be healthy.

A192239541264EB9837F9575D38E3017.description: Identifies a variety of healthy and unhealthy foods.

67E0F718C7854085AD58279AAE679348.description: Demonstrates a basic knowledge of the role of foods and nutrition in healthy development. Often requires adult guidance and supervision to make healthy eating choices.

1AE09784FF2846A3A1D81B1A5F95BC3B.description: Child develops knowledge and skills that help promote nutritious food choices and eating habits.

4595CE98B81D403F9E424CFA3B4843B2.description: Demonstrates increasing ability to take responsibility for participating in personal self-care skills, such as brushing teeth or getting dressed.

3D6278ED263A4EA487025BA508E31741.description: Washes hands with soap and water. Knows to do this before eating, after using the bathroom, or after blowing nose.

3C9D69BA1C9D492AAFD0587CD6ECC158.description: Shows an awareness of personal hygiene and self-care skills, such as telling an adult it is important to wash hands before eating. May not complete or exhibit these skills regularly without adult guidance and supervision.

687E24179283443A850B689123F307C7.description: Child demonstrates personal hygiene and self-care skills.

C2CA086FA62E4207BE07546C6157970E.description: Uses coordinated movements to complete complex tasks, such as cutting along a line, pouring, or buttoning.

DECEC88FF5664E2EB222184EFADF5826.description: Uses a pincer grip to hold and manipulate tools for writing, drawing, and painting.

0FB01EE3E2EA412C8B8DC05FADD65E7E.description: Easily coordinates hand and eye movements to carry out tasks, such as working on puzzles or stringing beads together.

7A05B6F6D7BC412CB6297F84A34C0BF3.description: Performs simple hand-eye tasks, such as drawing simple shapes like circles and cutting paper with scissors. May demonstrate limited precision and control in more complex tasks.

71C98F47CAB34D5AAF0E02D697980EA3.description: Child demonstrates increasing control, strength, and coordination of small muscles.

6E51E8D01C074FF2B6962AB1AD198C02.description: Changes directions when moving with little difficulty.

78AD569BB08C49DB95ECBA4E88A08464.description: When asked, can move own body in front of, to the side, or behind something or someone else, such as getting in line with other children.

EEFB61CF9BFF4FE4AA2006C5C543648F.description: Moves body in relation to objects to effectively perform tasks, such as moving body in position to kick a ball.

105D6B61CF704FF5A5C919F21F97775A.description: Demonstrates awareness of own body and other people’s space during interactions.

AA3E3F92634F4FB88AE449B9EF7E49A9.description: Somewhat aware of own body, space, and relationship to other objects. May have difficulty consistently coordinating motions and interactions with objects and other people.

B2F2586430254CA4B879A3548137F0DC.description: Child uses perceptual information to guide motions and interactions with objects and other people.

58F27D832CF649119A453F1C7E54B7C2.description: Demonstrates strength and stamina that allow for participation in a range of physical activities, such as running around playing tag.

E38D6E64B1BF40E587B30967A6D10E4F.description: Performs activities that combine and coordinate large muscle movements, including swinging on a swing, climbing a ladder, or dancing to music.

38F14FB36D834BF493AF3F344F22A2B7.description: Demonstrates balance in large-muscle movement, such as walking on a log without falling or balancing on one leg.

0966697FE28E4DD8B07FCCFAB570D12D.description: Balances, such as on one leg or a beam, for short periods with some assistance. Performs some skills, such as jumping for height and hopping, but these skills may not be consistently demonstrated. Engages in physical activity that requires strength and stamina for at least brief periods.

01E389E4B0234007A1F843A764F8A5D9.description: Child demonstrates control, strength, and coordination of large muscles.

1A17DA35DFE047CEB1F2D2F09127C0F5.description: Domain: Perceptual, Motor, and Physical Development

27705147DBFF4915B32714A747C4F6F8.description: Communicates results, solutions, and conclusions through a variety of methods, such as telling an adult that plants need water to grow or putting dots on a map that show the number of children from each country.

627D84F1441A43808063FF194658C261.description: With adult support, compares results to initial prediction and offers evidence as to why they do or do not work. Generates new testable questions based on results.

39560C8DF83E4700B17FEFEB8ABAC802.description: Draws conclusions, constructs explanations, and verbalizes cause and effect relationships.

A3BB0D5BE0984B828549CDF68F985690.description: Analyzes and interprets data and summarizes results of investigation.

28ED8A519C464C48A3A18AC4DEC7E1E6.description: With adult assistance, analyzes and interprets data. Draws conclusions and provides simple descriptions of results. For example, an adult suggests counting how many dolls can be supported by a bridge before it breaks and along with the children counts, “One, two, three dolls. What happened when we put on the next doll?” A child says, “The bridge broke!”

229AFBD5CA044032935FD9F8918498FD.description: Child analyzes results, draws conclusions, and communicates results.

8271CCAFE62E483EBCBE367DC770669A.description: Uses senses and simple tools to observe, gather, and record data, such as gathering data on where children’s families are from and creating a graph that shows the number of children from different countries.

A402CC3CA7BC455FB5E8C3CDB3EBAF3A.description: Implements steps and uses materials to explore testable questions, such as “Do plants need water to grow?” by planting seeds and giving water to some but not to others.

8619F3CC19A14DE3931DDE26F7D5AC96.description: Articulates steps to be taken and lists materials needed for an investigation or experiment.

B968BA5D5895498D84641210432853A9.description: With adult support, engages in simple investigations and experiments, such as building a “bridge” out of classroom materials and seeing how many dolls it will hold before it collapses. Records data with teacher assistance, mostly using pictures and marks on a page.

41CB969AB19F496D83E5D23FC45616C0.description: Child plans and conducts investigations and experiments.

23956D763E724883A25D718D478BC06D.description: Makes predictions and brainstorms solutions based on background knowledge and experiences, such as “I think that plants need water to grow.” or “I think adding yellow paint to purple will make brown.”

B02487E4A0C046A199F0C8BC38FEDCB4.description: Gathers information about a question by looking at books or discussing prior knowledge and observations.

31E0F5DB66F44C5E8AF50B1CB9FA5B1B.description: Asks questions that can be answered through an investigation, such as “What do plants need to grow?” or “What countries do the children in our class come from?”

B885DA29A45948C7BE3B5C60DAF0A141.description: Asks simple questions. Uses adults as primary resources to gather information about questions. With adult support and modeling, makes simple predictions, such as “I think that the golf ball will be heavier than the ping pong ball.”

CBE1B41C45904C39AF9BD596F803ED42.description: Child asks a question, gathers information, and makes predictions.

EACE274BCF594ED09470E9102E238015.description: Uses measurement tools, such as a ruler, balance scale, eye dropper, unit blocks, thermometer, or measuring cup, to quantify similarities and differences of observable phenomena.

4E909CCC790B4B02A89127C9ADC4EADF.description: Categorizes by sorting observable phenomena into groups based on attributes such as appearance, weight, function, ability, texture, odor, and sound.

7A8F5F2144D2404DBBFFC87DDC2917DB.description: Sorts objects into groups based on simple attributes, such as color. With support, uses measurement tools to quantify similarities and differences of observable phenomena, such as when a child scoops sand into two containers and with adult assistance, determines which container holds more scoops.

AF839688CE2B4C1E8B1218ED189C0C9C.description: Child compares and categorizes observable phenomena.

51464EAB0C3448D0AC374084BE7F0EFD.description: Uses scientific content words when investigating and describing observable phenomena, such as parts of a plant, animal, or object.

460D17A3EF204FCEA16DF87CC3042F65.description: Uses scientific practice words or signs, such as observe, describe, compare, contrast, question, predict, experiment, reflect, cooperate, or measure.

F111B4F5A99A40349CC28A6DA84CA713.description: Begins to use scientific vocabulary words with modeling and support from an adult. Sometimes repeats new words offered by adults.

9D9D8760731D4227821AEA2BA5A08791.description: Represents observable phenomena with pictures, diagrams, and 3-D models.

E9145760509F4832896D1C332E19EABD.description: Describes observable phenomena using adjectives and labels, such as lemons taste sour and play dough feels sticky.

713BB43463FF430FBFE7566607C1FD44.description: Uses observational tools to extend the five senses, such as a magnifying glass, microscope, binoculars, or stethoscope.

5E9972C809EA4CDC8872FCB32CE64224.description: Identifies the five senses (smell, touch, sight, sound, taste) and uses them to make observations.

C527B38E16AD49CC886A12E65D2815E7.description: Uses the five senses to observe objects, materials, organisms, and events. Provides simple verbal or signed descriptions. With adult support, represents observable phenomena, such as draws a picture.

66576DA672B0450B86896AF7D3BF6770.description: Child observes and describes observable phenomena (objects, materials, organisms, and events).

2D28C9C78EF34536B1E4926E189628B9.description: Correctly follows directions involving their own position in space, such as “Stand up” and “Move forward.”

E1141F79D7F94BFE94F482AD5CB3A079.description: Understands and uses language related to directionality, order, and the position of objects, including up/down, and in front/behind.

390A5AB6B4754D91A60EA485674585C1.description: Begins to understand spatial vocabulary. With adult support, follows directions involving their own position in space, such as “Stand up and stretch your arms to the sky.”

5000F1F9599E4CD4AD59A80452F7C370.description: Child explores the positions of objects in space.

34B778613F7D4EFDA9673F07212E5518.description: Creates and builds shapes from components.

6CAF40F59D5B4088B33EA75AB377F5FE.description: Analyzes, compares and sorts twoand three-dimensional shapes and objects in different sizes. Describes their similarities, differences, and other attributes, such as size and shape.

B463A1DD2C5E4ECBAD1E8AF4A145C6F2.description: Correctly names basic shapes regardless of size and orientation.

935710CC51674720880063EF91990A79.description: Names and describes shapes in terms of length of sides, number of sides, and number of angles.

D14BA909A839472FBFB9DECF2A5C6B21.description: Recognizes and names typical circle, square, and sometimes a triangle. With adult support, matches some shapes that are different sizes and orientations

2BC14F209BF941368808176FC65FA879.description: Child identifies, describes, compares, and composes shapes.

F44D6FCBEEDE49ADACB1716E3499345A.description: Uses comparative language, such as shortest, heavier, or biggest.

D2B47D79D0AF42DB8B91707DC4212EEA.description: Compares or orders up to 5 objects based on their measurable attributes, such as height or weight.

5ED239A51679478E974F45AF28801656.description: Measures using the same unit, such as putting together snap cubes to see how tall a book is.

64A3B8C9782F44A18816EF1C56D48A54.description: With adult support, begins to understand that attributes can be compared, such as one child can be taller than another child.

50E8F65C4DFF422ABF9D9676790D011A.description: Child measures objects by their various attributes using standard and non-standard measurement. Uses differences in attributes to make comparisons.

C1B46B8D4F8641459056033B86B01450.description: Identifies the core unit of sequentially repeating patterns, such as color in a sequence of alternating red and blue blocks.

C9F1CECAEEFD48599A7970BA34F62B71.description: Duplicates simple patterns in a different location than demonstrated, such as making the same alternating color pattern with blocks at a table that was demonstrated on the rug. Extends patterns, such as making an eight block tower of the same pattern that was demonstrated with four blocks.

47F195F5BB0B428FAC435C534739B0B6.description: Fills in missing elements of simple patterns.

EBB95665BBC34CF1BE817551DE02A223.description: Recognizes a simple pattern, and with adult assistance, fills in the missing element of a pattern, such as boy, girl, boy, girl, ___, girl. Duplicates and extends ABABAB patterns.

A26F3A21654847E1B4FD3E15EAB85C41.description: With adult assistance, begins to use counting on from the larger number for addition. For example, when adding a group of 3 and a group of 2, counts “One, two, three…” and then counts on “Four, five!” (keeping track with fingers). When counting back for subtraction such as taking away 3 from 5, counts, “Five, four, three…two!” (keeping track with fingers).

C65C2912397C4644B0B4B89DC1FD747F.description: Begins to add and subtract very small collections of objects with adult support. For example, the teacher says, “You have 3 grapes and get 1 more. How many in all?” Child counts out 3, then counts out 1 more, then counts all 4: “1, 2, 3, 4. I have 4!”

F2C71D4F848A4BFBB05D147690A6BDEF.description: Represents addition and subtraction in different ways, such as with fingers, objects, and drawings.

2A98F321121F439DA158B8643BE7DFB1.description: Child understands addition as adding to and understands subtraction as taking away from.

169DADC4AF4645EA80C2C4DADAA99108.description: Recognizes and, with support, writes some numerals up to 10.

C34E746A6F72450BB477D618FFAB2A9E.description: Associates a number of objects with a written numeral 0–5.

4CC3D010197F4B5A96862B260294AC4C.description: Begins to understand that a written numeral represents a quantity and may draw objects or use informal symbols to represent numbers.

9A5221EABCAB46019B20BE5DCF082A8F.description: Child associates a quantity with written numerals up to 5 and begins to write numbers.

E42701E50E074A92AC78B15238614333.description: Identifies and uses numbers related to order or position from first to tenth.

94C64892936E4693A32528BEB33EA173.description: Identifies whether the number of objects in one group is more than, less than, or the same as objects in another group for up to at least five objects.

EC58363F30E84611A2D98B44A21AE55B.description: Begins to accurately count and compare objects that are about the same size and are in small groups with adult assistance, such as counts a pile of 2 blocks and a pile of 4, and determines whether the piles have the same or different numbers of blocks. Identifies the first and second objects in a sequence.

966AC5AF3C48471D9D755CB10084DFA5.description: Understands that the last number said represents the number of objects in a set.

620CAA0BDC8042E9AC7E90DABF354D89.description: Understands that each successive number name refers to a quantity that is one larger.

2350DD1E6D3D4255A79B814F535F2834.description: Accurately counts as many as 5 objects in a scattered configuration.

167678BD2DBD401896F06154928CC504.description: Counts and answers “How many?” questions for approximately 10 objects.

43006CDA946D45329D4723EBA618E9A6.description: When counting objects, says or signs the number names in order, pairing one number word that corresponds with one object, up to at least 10.

AF5702B3F9E048F68678C2F299BADC1A.description: Begins to coordinate verbal counting with objects by pointing to or moving objects for small groups of objects laid in a line (referred to as one-to-one correspondence). Begins to understand that the last number represents how many objects are in a group (referred to as “cardinality”).

B19525A4455045DFA86C53824C48063E.description: Child understands the relationship between numbers and quantities.

42A46E6AE565456D946A85507D7CF382.description: Instantly recognizes, without counting, small quantities of up to 5 objects and says or signs the number.

6C15A9EF76BB43848B20E4ADB08D8656.description: Develops an understanding of what whole numbers mean. Begins to recognize the number of small objects in groups without counting (referred to as “subitizing”).

72CB2AC4358D4422A1B79876D2D14B1D.description: Child recognizes the number of objects in a small set.

BF6DA5A43A154B399D2593C074137EAA.description: Counts verbally or signs to at least 20 by ones.

D4CF95CBA2614E03AA57D9EA36C16C0E.description: Says or signs some number words in sequence (up to 10), starting with one. Understands that counting words are separate words, such as “one,” “two,” “three” versus “onetwothree”.

0342295F1E9A407393F66CEAC0D1CC2D.description: Child knows number names and the count sequence.

64776C764C7C4744B3BF2D57232FDFA7.description: Writes (draws, illustrates) for a variety of purposes and demonstrates evidence of many aspects of print conventions, such as creating a book that moves left to right.

F3145B3A99C348A1A7B0551BBA5E5C5B.description: Writes first name correctly or close to correctly.

1BAD02DF1160431BACD8CB8FE32837CA.description: Attempts to independently write some words using invented spelling, such as K for kite.

6C2D102181F643DFB63EA1C23F1B30F7.description: Shows an interest in copying simple words posted in the classroom.

E671EE76F33C4A2AAC580884B9BA7A04.description: Creates a variety of written products that may or may not phonetically relate to intended messages.

A40E5F5A47F4489D9B435677A752D575.description: Engages in writing activities that consist largely of drawing and scribbling. Begins to convey meaning. With modeling and support, writes some letter-like forms and letters.

C346F5746B244641BACA77548A8B4F0C.description: Child writes for a variety of purposes using increasingly sophisticated marks.

579433232CDA475E975166F6AE23EF33.description: Provides a summary of a story, highlighting a number of the key ideas in the story and how they relate.

22FA89B63EF140988D4B7D81B4D50B4A.description: Answers increasingly complex inferential questions that require making predictions based on multiple pieces of information from the story; inferring characters’ feelings or intentions; or providing evaluations of judgments that are grounded in the text.

8546D18F55634E7FAA928BC6C2360E47.description: Answers questions about details of a story with increasingly specific information, such as when asked “Who was Mary?” responds “She was the girl who was riding the horse and then got hurt.”

2ACCF6A8D59848FBB68B6DAC1500F130.description: Can answer basic questions about likes or dislikes in a book or story. Asks and answers questions about main characters or events in a familiar story. With modeling and support, makes predictions about events that might happen next.

DA78C5AD6BC049DCB80A956087AB009D.description: Child asks and answers questions about a book that was read aloud.

8F302CF1B1594EA3891167074C4C2114.description: Identifies characters and main events in books and stories.

3876123C7EE0408698AE0CF6099C6676.description: Tells fictional or personal stories using a sequence of at least 2–3 connected events.

FC888F90A4D742AC9A284E8E1419DD58.description: Re-tells or acts out a story that was read, putting events in the appropriate sequence, and demonstrating more sophisticated understanding of how events relate, such as cause and effect relationships.

0A8B94E10C6C498FB0AA77E4F94CD2C2.description: With support, may be able to tell one or two key events from a story or may act out a story with pictures or props.

DADF25C6E3344335A8528EC6C001D5FE.description: Child demonstrates an understanding of narrative structure through storytelling/re-telling.

78B44993A7464303A49E783AE25A466F.description: Knows the sounds associated with several letters.

3F967CF0258C4367990F338A15DD06E7.description: Shows an awareness of alphabet letters, such as singing the ABC song, recognizing letters from one’s name, or naming some letters that are encountered often.

BA7D8C5E1FED43499F6D4F1180B03CC9.description: Child identifies letters of the alphabet and produces correct sounds associated with letters.

82C5C6C1C8F24D2F95C46777E311561F.description: Identifies book parts and features, such as the front, back, title, and author.

72AE11F72F014A8AA4BFE7F0C8B5DA45.description: Begins to point to single-syllable words while reading simple, memorized texts.

DD57FC92702B48A48B5BA1149FEBE278.description: Understands that written words are made up of a group of individual letters.

19ACB7EC8EAE485AAEA9647A2D60EB2B.description: Understands that print is organized differently for different purposes, such as a note, list, or storybook.

A5061C5952704CB884ECA19E3ECD0AD1.description: Distinguishes print from pictures and shows an understanding that print is something meaningful, such as asking an adult “What does this say?” or “Read this.”

8495732D33F34962B1BC14CCF2EDC04B.description: Child demonstrates an understanding of how print is used (functions of print) and the rules that govern how print works (conventions of print).

2234B41E99D94BF7B2FB17A83EF861AE.description: Provides a word that fits with a group of words sharing an initial sound, with adult support, such as “Sock, Sara, and song all start with the /s/ sound. What else starts with the /s/ sound?”

EF285FA6D9C6471795AFC84866FCE169.description: Produces the beginning sound in a spoken word, such as “Dog begins with /d/.”

7D144AB2EFB5400B876B7D3E862E1751.description: Provides one or more words that rhyme with a single given target, such as “What rhymes with log?”

2F1738004F3145A9BDBF78CCC3A68ABF.description: Shows rote imitation and enjoyment of rhyme and alliteration. With support, distinguishes when two words rhyme and when two words begin with the same sound.

61FBA7EF211B4DAB9B03FC3CE49FF09A.description: Child demonstrates awareness that spoken language is composed of smaller segments of sound.

FE4197447D6946008660981FAAF8C95C.description: Shows an ability to distinguish similar words, such as “I don’t like it, I love it!” or “It’s more than tall, it’s gigantic” or “It’s so cold, it’s frosty.”

CC745C5558AB49BC897F850C70912713.description: Identifies key common antonyms, such as black/white or up/down. Identifies 1–2 synonyms for very familiar words, such as glad or happy.

4379EAE071774B89A38733A55969ED97.description: Identifies shared characteristics among people, places, things, or actions, such as identifying that both cats and dogs are furry and have four legs.

A4D9E7D2206C4BE6A3F049EB032624E5.description: Discusses new words in relation to known words and word categories, such as “It fell to the bottom when it sank” or “When you hop it’s like jumping on one leg” or “The bear and fox are both wild animals.”

C180E6F92AD84EC3A74860CF053642E4.description: Categorizes words or objects, such as sorting a hard hat, machines, and tools into the construction group, or giving many examples of farm animals.

39788031DFCC40F2BD340BB97E103A71.description: Typically uses known words in the correct context and, with support, shows an emerging understanding of how words are related to broader categories, such as sorting things by color.

66310D28B6CA428FA6F40960F50BE74F.description: Child shows understanding of word categories and relationships among words.

C54E6C7E59224BB1918CC81D0985CFBD.description: With support, forms guesses about the meaning of new words from context clues.

018698E96F2A4556966A26564850E959.description: With multiple exposures, uses new domain-specific vocabulary during activities, such as using the word “cocoon” when learning about the lifecycle of caterpillars, or “cylinder” when learning about 3-D shapes.

FDE0E4C05AE44B4A870C24EACA01DA02.description: Shows recognition of and/or familiarity with key domain-specific words heard during reading or discussions.

FC2921AC81C742ACB70BA39B2EC89806.description: Demonstrates the use of multiple (2–3) new words or signs a day during play and other activities.

20CB04A4DBEC4D73A2131A77EAE4A222.description: Shows a rapid increase in acquisition of new vocabulary words that describe actions, emotions, things, or ideas that are meaningful within the everyday environment. Uses new vocabulary words to describe relations among things or ideas. Shows repetition of new words offered by adults.

FFF36735CD964610A95B4FFE1DB5C178.description: Child understands and uses a wide variety of words for a variety of purposes.

7F0DF8B314DA41BC8DE43F2B10E0CCCD.description: Can produce and organize multiple sentences on a topic, such as giving directions or telling a story, including information about the past or present or things not physically present, and answer a variety of question types.

C780B27D11504AB4B80D42117CA93779.description: Typically, uses complete sentences of more than 5 words with complex structures, such as sentences involving sequence and causal relations.

979337E564684470ADCC79D5953A36CF.description: Communicates clearly enough to be understood by adults across a range of situations. Pronunciation errors and grammatical errors are isolated and infrequent. Shows proficiency with prepositions, regular/irregular past tense, possessives, and noun-verb agreement.

976F9F7BC7704531BEB6582FF2829AAC.description: Communicates clearly enough to be understood by familiar adults, but may make some pronunciation and grammatical errors. Typically uses 3–5 word phrases/sentences when communicating. With some prompting, can offer multiple (2–3) pieces of information on a single topic.

68E36005FEBB4FDBA8483BE1020EBBE3.description: Child expresses self in increasingly long, detailed, and sophisticated ways.

8FE632B7F18B4BB99EC26A524D80D751.description: With increasing independence, matches the tone and volume of expression to the content and social situation, such as by using a whisper to tell a secret.

34858745ADF8489DA8839F7D8FA2F95B.description: Maintains multi-turn conversations with adults, other children, and within larger groups by responding in increasingly sophisticated ways, such as asking related questions or expressing agreement.

C5C489F0486540A684BA57373248AF1C.description: Engages in conversations with adults, other children, or within the group setting lasting 2–3 conversational turns, and, with support, will sometimes use appropriate tone and volume for different situations.

03A4FA7D34B94C9F834360A955FBFD59.description: Child understands, follows, and uses appropriate social and conversational rules.

B0F7159606EF48909EBC4318293FA294.description: Children who are DLLs may switch between their languages.

939954EF3A7C4169BEEABC853F3DF52B.description: Uses language, spoken or sign, to clarify a word or statement when misunderstood.

92DA73C7AE06444A814FF78A1E54EEBE.description: Usually provides sufficient detail in order to get needs met, such as explaining a point of difficulty in a task or sharing a request from home with the teacher.

CB28F584A6384198B4602BED48E1BDEA.description: Uses language, spoken or sign, for different purposes and is sometimes able to provide sufficient detail to get needs met from a variety of adults.

500CFC8306854F0AAB0FAFFBC09C9F73.description: Child varies the amount of information provided to meet the demands of the situation.

EF947407988B483C9D2C1AD5AAA7D652.description: Shows understanding, such as nodding or gestures, in response to the content of books read aloud, stories that are told, or lengthy explanations given on a topic. Children who are DLLs may demonstrate more complex communication and language in their home language than in English.

79642892D68343F19AE8A9B7B922B754.description: Shows an understanding of talk related to the past or future.
